Colin has a thought: "If you watch a replay of Mike Hussey's dismissal you can see that his bat was right behind his toe when the ball hit his toe. The LBW law states that the batsman is out if the ball hits the batsman's body and "but for the interception, the ball would have hit the wicket." In Hussey's case the ball would NOT have the wicket - it would have hit his bat. Therefore he should be NOT OUT."

Shantanu from the USA has asked us the difference between the hook and the pull. As far as I know: the pull is played to a ball around waist height, while the hook is played to a short delivery between chest and head height. The hook is more risky because the ball is hit high in the air.

Naveed has another doubt: "What's the difference between fast, medium fast, and fast medium?" Well, the first one is obviously quicker than the second and third. I think medium-fast and fast-medium can be interchanged. It includes, I would think, a whole range of bowlers between 130 and 140.
